post_text:
ATTENTION HIGH SCHOOL REMOTE PAPER LEARNERS:

If you are a remote student completing assignments on paper you must turn in assignments on Tuesday and Thursday. On Tuesday you turn in work that was due for completion Thursday, Friday, and Monday. On Thursday you turn in work that was due for completion Tuesday and Wednesday. Do not wait until the two weeks to turn everything in at once. You need to turn in work weekly.

Si eres un estudiante remoto que completa las tareas en papel, debes entregar las tareas los martes y jueves. El martes entrega el trabajo que debía completarse el jueves, viernes y lunes. El jueves entregará el trabajo que debía completarse el martes y miércoles. No espere hasta las dos semanas para entregar todo de una vez. Necesita entregar el trabajo semanalmente.

Vaccinations and Screenings

All students enrolled at NSCISD must have proof of current immunizations prior to the school start date of 9/1/2020. This includes students enrolled in the remote online option. All students will be required to have vision, hearing and spinal screenings, including students enrolled in the remote online option. Screenings for off-campus students will be by appointment only in order to follow social distancing guidelines. Scheduling information will be posted as it becomes available. Please contact your campus nurse if you have questions.

You will be receiving a letter in the mail in the next few days explaining the P-EBT. Every student in our district receives free breakfast and lunch no matter how many people live in the home or what the family's income is.

If you already receive SNAP benefits you DO NOT need to fill out the application.

Here is the link to the quick and easy application. It does not require a student Social Security number or lunch numbers, but if you have those available it might help speed up the process of receiving benefits:

https://yourtexasbenefits.com/Learn/PEBT

If you would like more in-depth information about the P-EBT program or free and reduced lunch program available to your children there information and resources on the Health and Human Services website.

Our Senior signs are being moved to their new home at the entry of the Nixon-Smiley HS track, where they will be proudly displayed as a "Senior Walk." Signs will remain there until after graduation. At that time, we will make arrangements to give them to the Seniors.

With this exciting news, we also want to let you know that the NS track is reopening as of 05/05/2020 at 6 p.m. Please feel free to come by and enjoy a walk while celebrating the success of the Senior Class of 2020. We do encourage you to maintain social distancing and other safety measures, but taking pictures is welcomed and encouraged.

El distrito escolar de Nixon-Smiley CISD no está apoyando o alentando ninguna campaña en las redes sociales "Adopta a un Senior". Estamos muy preocupados por la seguridad de nuestros estudiantes y nos preocupa que publicar fotos y / o compartir información personal, incluidas las direcciones de los hogares, pueda ser riesgoso.

Sin embargo, recomendamos encarecidamente a cualquiera que desee proporcionar un regalo o una tarjeta a nuestros graduantes que trabajen con nuestros comerciantes locales que crean Registros de Graduantes. En el pasado, esto incluía a Main Drug, The Flower Tubb, y Western Store de Nixon. El uso de esta opción no solo demostraría a nuestros graduantes que usted se preocupa, sino que también respaldaría a las empresas locales.

Le avisaremos cuando esos registros estén listos y cómo participar.

Si otra empresa o negocio local quiere participar, comuníquese con el superintendente a cathy.lauer@nixonsmiley.net para que pueda ser incluido en futuros comunicados de prensa.

post_text:
ATTENTION NSCISD COMMUNITY
Nixon-Smiley CISD is not supporting or encouraging any social media “Adopt a Senior” campaigns. We are very concerned about the safety of our students and worry that posting pictures and/or sharing personal information, including home addresses, could be risky.

However, we do strongly encourage anyone who wants to provide a gift or card to our Seniors to work with our local merchants who set up Senior Registries. In the past, this has included Main Drug, The Flower Tubb, and Western Store Nixon. Using this option would not only show our Seniors that you care, but it would support local businesses.

We will let you know when those registers are ready and how to participate.

If any other local businesses are participating, please contact the superintendent at cathy.lauer@nixonsmiley.net so you can be included in future press releases.

Parents of Gifted and Talented Students,
Nixon-Smiley CISD is committed to providing educational opportunities to students identified as Gifted and Talented. The links below have resources for enrichment to continue engaging children in the learning process at home. They should have also received this link from their GT tutorial/pull-out teacher. Students should pick and choose different activities based on interests. These activities can be done when a break is needed from their remote learning or if they finish their remote learning early on in the week. These activities are not required.

Elementary: https://sites.google.com/nixonsmiley.net/nsegt/home

Middle School: https://sites.google.com/nixonsmiley.net/msgt/home

High School: https://sites.google.com/nixonsmiley.net/hsgt/home

If you have any questions, please contact the Gifted and Talented Coordinator, Brittany Rogers at rogersb@nixonsmiley.net.

IMPORTANT ANNOUNCEMENT

As you are probably aware, the COVID-19 situation has continued to evolve. New cases have been identified in and around our area. With this in mind, Nixon-Smiley CISD has made the difficult decision to extend the closure of our campuses and facilities until further notice. However, meal delivery and remote instruction will continue. See our web page at www.nixonsmiley.net for information on those activities.

This decision will be re-evaluated as more information becomes available. A formal update will be posted during the week of April 20th. If it appears possible at that time, we will begin announcing procedures and a date for a return to normal operations. If we are unable to plan for a return, we will instead provide information on year-end events like graduation.

Thank you for your support and cooperation as we ensure that all members of the community in Nixon-Smiley CISD stay safe and healthy.

~*~*~*~*~*~*~*~*~*~*~*~
Cathy L. Lauer, Ph.D.
Superintendent
Nixon-Smiley CISD
(830) 582-1536 ext. 103
cathy.lauer@nixonsmiley.net

The Nixon-Smiley CISD counselors would like to support our students in the best way possible during this time. We have created a website that gives our students and parents resources for each campus, and it gives them a way to contact us if they need to speak to us. We will be adding to the website throughout the duration of the quarantine. We will not have academic assignments, but resources on how to cope with the uncertainty and anxiety that they may be feeling. Please feel free to reach out to any of us if you need anything or have any questions.

https://sites.google.com/nixonsmiley.net/mrs-clardy/middle-school-resources

Stock show season continues, and this year's Nixon-Smiley Livestock Show is right around the corner!

Wilson County News is promoting the show in the March 4 issue. Help celebrate the hard work of all the FFA and 4-H students, by sharing photos of this year's exhibitors preparing their projects or practicing for the show.

Send your photos, including the student's name, age, grade, and competition(s) they're entering to: reader@wcn-online.com, putting NIXON SHOW 2020 in the subject line.

Good luck to this year's exhibitors!

(WCN file photo from 2019 Nixon-Smiley show)

post_text: Nixon-Smiley FCCLA had an exciting couple of days at the Region 5 Texas Association of Family, Career, Community Leaders of America conference. Students competed in Chapter Service Project, Nutrition and Wellness, and Serving up Success, as well as, participated in Family and Consumer Sciences Assessments, represented NS FCCLA in Spotlight on Projects, and served as helpers and room consultants. We came away with state qualifiers in Serving up Success and FCSAs. William Filla ran for a regional officer position and was elected. He will represent Nixon-Smiley and all of Region 5 as the VP of Achievement in the coming year!!! We are super proud of all of their accomplishments!
text: Nixon-Smiley FCCLA had an exciting couple of days at the Region 5 Texas Association of Family, Career, Community Leaders of America conference. We came away with state qualifiers in Serving up Success and FCSAs. William Filla ran for a regional officer position and was elected. He will represent Nixon-Smiley and all of Region 5 as the VP of Achievement in the coming year!!! We are super proud of all of their accomplishments!

post_text: Nixon-Smiley Family, Careers, and Community Leaders of America are seeking help! The local FCCLA Chapter has started a hygiene closet for middle and high school students. These products and items are available through the NSCISD #mustangCARE. We are in need of additional supplies to add to the collection, so we are seeking donations. Supplies can vary from shampoos and conditioners to deodorants to oral hygiene products, as well as feminine hygiene products. All donations can be dropped off at the high school office or in Ms. Brown's classroom. We will also be accepting donations at the basketball game on Tuesday, Jan. 21st. Contact Ms. Brown at the high school for more information.

post_text:
NS ELEMENTARY 4th GRADE CAREER FAIR: DAY TWO
Our second day of Career Fair was as amazing as the first! Today we welcomed Blake Casteter from the Gonzales Fire Department to talk about being a firefighter/EMT. We had Texas State Trooper Krueger here to talk with us about what it takes to become a state trooper and the different kinds of jobs troopers can have. Mechanical engineer Richard Babbs joined us to talk about the many different kinds of engineering careers. Texas Game Warden Dustin Balfanz from Gonzales County came to talk about his career. Finally, Chef Juan Munoz joined us to discuss his career and what it involves. We learned so much from our Career Fair participants. We would like to send out a huge "thank you" to today's presenters!! Our third year is in the books!

Mechanical engineer Richard Babbs joined us to talk about the many different kinds of engineering careers. Texas Game Warden Dustin Balfanz from Gonzales County came to talk about his career. Finally, Chef Juan Munoz joined us to discuss his career and what it involves. We learned so much from our Career Fair participants. We would like to send out a huge "thank you" to today's presenters!! Our third year is in the books!

post_text:
NS ELEMENTARY 4th GRADE CAREER FAIR: DAY ONE
We had a great first day of Career Fair in 4th grade today! We started out with a presentation from GVEC and their linemen. Then we had a presentation from Mrs. Atkins on being a school principal. Wildlife biologist Jamie Killian joined us to talk about what her amazing career involves. Mr. Ortiz came from Victoria College Gonzales Center to talk about his job and the different degrees and certifications offered on their campus. Kaylee Wood joined us from Pawsitively Devine Mobil Grooming Service and groomed one of her dogs for us. Dr. Lauer joined us to talk about being a school superintendent, and Mr. Jimenez came to talk about other school jobs. Lastly, Kelsey Robinson presented the cosmetology career, showing us her incredible talent. We would like to extend a huge "thank you" to all presenters today! We are excited to hear tomorrow's presentations!

IMPORTANT TRUNK OR TREAT ANNOUNCEMENT
Due to the expected inclement of weather, NSCISD is disappointed to announce that we have cancelled our annual Trunk or Treat Festival scheduled for Wednesday, October 30th. We appreciate all who planned to be a part of this event and apologize for having to make this difficult decision. However, we believe it is in the best interest of everyone to stay inside where it is dry and warm. We look forward to resuming this tradition next year.

Today, the Nixon-Smiley Education Foundation awarded $11,379.00 to the Teachers of Nixon-Smiley CISD. This money will be spent innovative and engaging learning activities for the students in the district. We cannot wait to see the exciting activities that the teachers have planned in action.

If you are interested in investing in our future, please comment below and we will let you know how you can make a difference.

post_text: Thank you Smiley City Marshals!!
shared_text:
Smiley City Marshal's Office
August 26, 2019 at 8:47 PM ·

Good afternoon everyone. Today we were asked by a citizen why we were at the Elementary Campus and if there was something going on parents needed to know about. After being asked that question we thought maybe we would explain our presence on campus. Periodically you may see a patrol unit parked in front of the school and a deputy walking the halls. This is something we began at the beginning of school last year when we increased our campus presence only to ensure the continued safety of students and staff. Again this is just a small part of our efforts to keep NSCISD students and staff #mustangSAFE
